To generate a custom ID for your NestJS application, you can define a function that generates the ID and then use it when inserting data into your database.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

1. Define the function that generates the ID:
```typescript
function generateId(): string {
  // implement your custom ID generation logic here
  return 'your_custom_id';
}
```
2. In your database schema or entity, define the ID column with a default value of the generated ID:
```typescript
import { Entity, Column, PrimaryGeneratedColumn } from 'typeorm';

@Entity()
export class YourEntity {
  @PrimaryGeneratedColumn('uuid')
  id: string;

  @Column()
  name: string;

  @Column({ default: () => generateId() })
  customId: string;
}
```
In the example above, the `customId` column is defined with a default value that is a function call to the `generateId()` function.

Now when you insert a new row into the database, the `customId` column will be automatically populated with the value returned by the `generateId()` function.

Note that this approach may not be suitable for high-concurrency applications, as there is a possibility of collisions if the same ID is generated by the function for multiple rows. In that case, you may want to consider using a UUID or another globally unique identifier.

Sure, here's an example of a `ValidationPipe` in NestJS:
```typescript
import { Injectable, PipeTransform, ArgumentMetadata, BadRequestException } from '@nestjs/common';
import { validate } from 'class-validator';
import { plainToClass } from 'class-transformer';

@Injectable()
export class ValidationPipe implements PipeTransform<any> {
  async transform(value: any, metadata: ArgumentMetadata) {
    const { metatype } = metadata;
    if (!metatype || !this.toValidate(metatype)) {
      return value;
    }
    const object = plainToClass(metatype, value);
    const errors = await validate(object);
    if (errors.length > 0) {
      throw new BadRequestException('Validation failed');
    }
    return value;
  }

  private toValidate(metatype: any): boolean {
    const types = [String, Boolean, Number, Array, Object];
    return !types.includes(metatype);
  }
}
```
In this example, the `ValidationPipe` is used to validate the input data of a route before it's passed to the controller method. The pipe first checks if the metadata includes a `metatype` (i.e., a class constructor), and if so, it uses the `class-transformer` library to transform the input data into an instance of the `metatype` class. Then, it uses the `class-validator` library to validate the object, throwing a `BadRequestException` if there are any errors.

You can use this pipe by adding it as a global or route-scoped pipe in your module's configuration:
```typescript
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
import { APP_PIPE } from '@nestjs/core';
import { ValidationPipe } from './pipes/validation.pipe';
import { UsersController } from './users.controller';

@Module({
  controllers: [UsersController],
  providers: [
    {
      provide: APP_PIPE,
      useClass: ValidationPipe,
    },
  ],
})
export class AppModule {}
```
This adds the `ValidationPipe` to the global scope of your application, meaning it will be applied to all routes by default. If you only want to apply the pipe to specific routes, you can add it as a provider to the controller itself:
```typescript
import { Controller, Post, Body, UsePipes } from '@nestjs/common';
import { ValidationPipe } from './pipes/validation.pipe';
import { CreateUserDto } from './dto/create-user.dto';
import { UsersService } from './users.service';

@Controller('users')
export class UsersController {
  constructor(private readonly usersService: UsersService) {}

  @Post()
  @UsePipes(ValidationPipe)
  async createUser(@Body() createUserDto: CreateUserDto) {
    return this.usersService.createUser(createUserDto);
  }
}
```
In this example, the `ValidationPipe` is applied only to the `createUser` route using the `@UsePipes` decorator.

